Assignment 5¶

In this assignment, you'll scrape text from The California Aggie and then analyze the text.

The Aggie is organized by category into article lists. For example, there's a Campus News list, Arts & Culture list, and Sports list. Notice that each list has multiple pages, with a maximum of 15 articles per page.

The goal of exercises 1.1 - 1.3 is to scrape articles from the Aggie for analysis in exercise 1.4.

Exercise 1.1. Write a function that extracts all of the links to articles in an Aggie article list. The function should:

  • Have a parameter url for the URL of the article list.

  • Have a parameter page for the number of pages to fetch links from. The default should be 1.

  • Return a list of aricle URLs (each URL should be a string).

Test your function on 2-3 different categories to make sure it works.

Hints:

  • Be polite to The Aggie and save time by setting up requests_cache before you write your function.

  • Start by getting your function to work for just 1 page. Once that works, have your function call itself to get additional pages.

  • You can use lxml.html or BeautifulSoup to scrape HTML. Choose one and use it throughout the entire assignment.

def scrape_it(url,pages=1):
    urls = list()
    for times in range(1,pages + 1):
        page = 'page/%d/' % times
        qurl = requests.get(url+page)
        soup = BeautifulSoup(qurl.text, "lxml")
        for article in soup.find_all('article'):
            link = article.find_all('a')
            urls.append(link[0].get('href'))
    return urls

Hints:

  • The author line is always the last line of the last paragraph.

  • Python 2 displays some Unicode characters as \uXXXX. For instance, \u201c is a left-facing quotation mark. You can convert most of these to ASCII characters with the method call (on a string)

    .translate({ 0x2018:0x27, 0x2019:0x27, 0x201C:0x22, 0x201D:0x22, 0x2026:0x20 })

    If you're curious about these characters, you can look them up on this page, or read more about what Unicode is.

def get_info(url):
    qurl = requests.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(qurl.text, "lxml")
    info = dict.fromkeys(['author','text','title','url'])
    info['url'] = url
    for i in soup.find_all(['b','strong']):
        if "Written By" in i.getText() or "Written by" in i.getText():
            info['author'] = i.getText()
    info['title'] = soup.find_all('h1',class_='entry-title')[0].string.translate({ 0x2018:0x27, 0x2019:0x27, 0x201C:0x22, 0x201D:0x22, 0x2026:0x20 })
    text =  soup.find_all('div',itemprop = 'articleBody')[0].find_all('span')
    form_text = list()
    for i in text:
        form_text.append(i.string)
    form_text = unicode.join(u'\n',map(unicode,form_text))
    info['text'] = form_text.translate({ 0x2018:0x27, 0x2019:0x27, 0x201C:0x22, 0x201D:0x22, 0x2026:0x20 })
    return info

def really_custom_function():
    urls_from_campus = scrape_it('https://theaggie.org/campus/',4)
    urls_from_city = scrape_it('https://theaggie.org/city/',4)
    df = pandas.DataFrame()
    for i in urls_from_campus:
        x = get_info(i)
        x['cat'] = 1
        df = df.append(x,ignore_index = True)
    for j in urls_from_city:
        y = get_info(j)
        y['cat'] = 0
        df = df.append(y,ignore_index = True)
    return df

Exercise 1.4. Use the Aggie corpus to answer the following questions. Use plots to support your analysis.

  • What topics does the Aggie cover the most? Do city articles typically cover different topics than campus articles?

  • What are the titles of the top 3 pairs of most similar articles? Examine each pair of articles. What words do they have in common?

  • Do you think this corpus is representative of the Aggie? Why or why not? What kinds of inference can this corpus support? Explain your reasoning.

Hints:

  • The nltk book and scikit-learn documentation may be helpful here.

  • You can determine whether city articles are "near" campus articles from the similarity matrix or with k-nearest neighbors.

  • If you want, you can use the wordcloud package to plot a word cloud. To install the package, run

    conda install -c https://conda.anaconda.org/amueller wordcloud

    in a terminal. Word clouds look nice and are easy to read, but are less precise than bar plots.

  1. As expected, the wordcloud shows that the most covered topics pertain to UC Davis, the City of Davis, and the surrounding community. It also frequent topics include ASUCD, Students, California and Presidents. From the wordcloud it seems campus news is focused on the students of UC Davis, while city news is focused on sacremento and the city of Davis. Using kNN we find the error rate to be only about .17(with small k) which means campus and city news are sufficiently different.
  1. The top 3 pairs of articles are:

"2017 ASUCD Winter Elections — Meet the Candidates" and "UC Davis holds first mental health conference"

"Russell Boulevard intramural fields withdrawn from 2017-2027 Long Range Development Plan" and "2017 ASUCD Winter Elections — Meet the Candidates"

"Nov. 8 2016: An Election Day many may never forget" and "2017 ASUCD Winter Elections — Meet the Candidates"

The first pair have the words health, campus, student, major, Davis, and platform, among others.

The second pair have the words Housing, UC Davis, Russel, major, field and year, among others

The third pair have year, Davis, major, prop, state, and passed, among others.

  1. This corpus is indicative of the aggie because a lot of the results are what we expect. The most popular terms from the campus news revolve around UC Davis, the students, and student government. The city news revolves around news from the City of Davis, as well as news from the nearby city of Sacremento. Using this corpus, we can catagories between city and campus news with an error rate of around 17%.

stemmer = PorterStemmer().stem

tokenize = nltk.word_tokenize

def stem(tokens,stemmer = PorterStemmer().stem):
    return [stemmer(w.lower()) for w in tokens]

def lemmatize(text):
    return stem(tokenize(text))

    except NameError:
        toks = s
    for tok in s:

        except KeyError:
            textd[tok] = [fid]

k_max = 20
nbrs = NearestNeighbors(n_neighbors=k_max).fit(tfs)
err_list = []

for k in xrange(1,k_max+1,2):
    neighmat = nbrs.kneighbors_graph(n_neighbors=k)
    pred_lab = (neighmat.dot(df['cat']) > k/2.)*1 
    err =  np.mean(pred_lab != df['cat'])
    err_list.append(err)
    
plt.plot(range(1,k_max + 1,2),err_list)
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Error Rate')
